litaristic narratives. Four key narrative roles have beenselected - woman as helpmeet, woman as lover, woman as victim, and woman as spiritual model - in order to illustrate some major changes in the social status of women that took place during the period of this popular genre's existence. These poems are a key witness to the final stages of the chansons de geste before they were overtaken by the new fashion for the fictions of courtly romance. Apart from "The Capture of Orange", which has never been translated into modern English verse, none of the poems have yet appeared in English translation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChansons de gestevTranslations into English. 0aEpic poetry, FrenchvTranslations into English. 0aWomen in literature. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aChansons de Geste.  aFrench Cultural History.  aFrench Epic.  aHeroines in Literature.  aMedieval French Literature.  aMedieval Heroines.  aMichael Newth.1 aNewth, Michael A.H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178744628140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787446281423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787446281/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles